The scene is laid in a public street in Athens (cf. 30, 66, 1072) in which stand the houses of Theoropides (or Theo- propides3) and Simo. The action lasts from early morning⁴ till late in the asternoon : cf. notes on Ι. 1, Ι. 2, Ι. 3, I. 4, and lines 579 redito huc circiter meridiem, 651 iam adpetit meri- dies, 966 uide sis ne sorte ad merendam quopiam deuorterzlr. Between the two houses, which occupy the back of the stage, is the opening of a narrow side-street (angiportum, cf. 1046), employed in several passages of the play as a place from which the conversation on the stage may be overheard.
